<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP SOCCER '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; APPARENTLY, IT'S HOW YOU 
PLAYED THE GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SIMON BARNES, The Times of London 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Plucky little United States of America! This gallant little nation battled 
against the odds, defied the might of Switzerland and drew; took on the 
overwhelming superiority of Colombia and, incredibly, won. But despite its 
battling defeat against Romania, this minnow of a country has almost certainly 
qualified for the round of 16; only a series of truly weird events can prevent 
it. 
</P>
<P>
 This will keep home interest in the tournament alive for another week, which 
is some kind of result. America's likely opponents? Brazil or Germany. In one 
sense, a match against the former would be a perfect result for football; if 
watching an increasingly impressive Brazil does not give this country a taste 
for footy, nothing will. But I cannot see America relishing the sight of seeing 
its team overwhelmed by Brazil and the beautiful game. Can America find the 
beauty that lies in defeat, especially in defeat by the overwhelmingly superior 
opponent? 
</P>
</TEXT>
