<HEADLINE>
<P>
SMOKING DEBATE REACHES BALLOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A smoking measure sponsored by the Philip Morris tobacco company will be on 
California's Nov. 8 election ballot, state election officials said.Acting 
Secretary of State Tony Miller said the measure had well over the required 
384,974 voter signatures to qualify for the ballot. The initiative would create 
statewide smoking regulations but preempt tougher, local anti-smoking laws. 
Health groups have accused backers of misleading voters. 
</P>
