<HEADLINE>
<P>
DOWNTIME: BODY WATCH; AT HOME ON THE SEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sailing alone soothes me because the sea is fair, not cruel.It judges only 
your ability. It does not care who or what you are. It does not ask your age, 
color, sex, address, sexual orientation, education or IQ, but only your 
competence. It requires only that you can sail. If you can, you survive. If you 
can't, better stay ashore. That's fair, more fair than most of us experience on 
land. And refreshing. 
</P>
<P>
 -- C.E. ZOERNER JR., Manhattan Beach 
</P>
