<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: NORTH HOLLYWOOD; FREE PROGRAM OFFERS QUAKE TIPS TO SENIORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ED BOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Senior citizens can get free advice and help in preparing for earthquakes 
under a new program set up by the Valley Storefront Multiservice Center for 
Seniors in North Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had so many seniors who were so devastated by the earthquake, who lost 
their homes and belongings," said Rena Snyder, a casework supervisor with the 
Valley Storefront, which is run by the Jewish Family Service of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 "The idea is to go into their homes and help them protect themselves in the 
next one," she added. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the new Earthquake Survival Project, the Valley Storefront will send out 
volunteers to visit the homes of seniors and give suggestions about needed 
supplies. 
</P>
<P>
 Volunteers also will help them determine the safest places in their residence 
during a quake. 
</P>
<P>
 "They look around the home and see what can be done for protection -- for 
instance, if a mirror is over the bed, or other things that should be moved to 
a safer area," Snyder said. 
</P>
<P>
 At the end of the visit, the volunteers will give the seniors an earthquake 
preparedness kit, which includes items such as a flashlight, water and a first 
aid kit. 
</P>
<P>
 Snyder said it is hoped that the visits will alleviate some of the anxiety 
seniors have felt since the Jan. 17 Northridge earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 The program is open to people 60 and older who live in the San Fernando 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 To schedule a visit, call Phyllis Waxman at the Valley Storefront in North 
Hollywood at (818) 984-1380. ED BOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062894-0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 055580 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 28, 1994, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
