<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGE FACES TRIAL IN MOLESTATION CASE; COURTS: CHARGES HAVE BEEN REDUCED IN 
CASE INVOLVING ATTORNEY WHO SAYS STANLEY SAMUEL FEINSTEIN FONDLED HER IN HIS 
OFFICE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE TAMAKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A trial date was set Monday for a veteran worker's compensation judge on 
misdemeanor charges of sexually molesting an attorney in his Van Nuys chambers, 
after another judge refused to reinstate felony charges against him. 
</P>
<P>
 Judge Stanley Samuel Feinstein, 61, faces one count each of unlawful touching 
and false imprisonment for allegedly fondling a 40-year-old attorney during a 
March 28 visit to his office. 
</P>
<P>
 The district attorney's office originally charged Feinstein with felony counts 
of false imprisonment and sexual battery, but those charges were reduced to 
misdemeanors following a preliminary hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Lance A. Ito on Monday denied a prosecutor's 
bid to reinstate the felony charges and set Aug. 5 as the date for Feinstein's 
trial to start in Los Angeles Municipal Court. 
</P>
<P>
 If convicted, Feinstein faces a maximum of a year in jail for each of the 
misdemeanor counts, compared to a maximum four years in prison he would have 
faced on the sexual battery charge and three years on the charge of false 
imprisonment by violence. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, another judge ruled that the Los Angeles County district attorney's 
office could continue to prosecute Feinstein, denying a motion by defense 
attorneys to remove the district attorney's office from the case. 
</P>
<P>
 State officials fired Feinstein from his job last month after he refused to 
cooperate with an internal investigation into the alleged incident. 
</P>
<P>
 During the preliminary hearing, the female attorney testified that Feinstein 
had invited her to his office at the State Office Building in the Van Nuys 
Government Center so that he could tell her the date of a lecture. 
</P>
<P>
 The woman testified that as she was about to leave, Feinstein told her to 
close the door because he had something else to tell her and, after she did, he 
attacked her by slamming her body up against a wall and fondling her. 
</P>
</TEXT>
