<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHERE ARE THEY NOW? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times staff writer David W. Myers catches up with former Dodgers and 
Angels.GARY CARTER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Carter played only one season in Los Angeles, 1991, but he got into 101 games 
while platooning with fellow catcher Mike Scioscia. The former three-sport 
standout at Sunny Hills High in Fullerton was signed as a free agent the next 
year by Montreal -- where he had begun his career in 1974 -- and retired at the 
end of the 1992 season having caught more games, 2,056, than any other player 
in National League history. Carter, 40, lives in Florida and is the color 
commentator on the Marlins' telecasts. 
</P>
